The '''Annals of Quedlinburg''' ({{lang-lat|Saxonicae Annales Quedlinburgenses}}, {{lang-de|Quedlinburger Annalen}}) were written between 1008 and 1030 in the [[convent]] of [[Quedlinburg Abbey]]. In recent years a consensus has emerged that the annalist was a woman.<ref name=warner>{{cite book|last=[[Thietmar of Merseburg]]|author2=David Warner|title=Ottonian Germany:The Chronicon of Thietmar of Merseburg|year=2001|pages=43|isbn=0-7190-4926-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RQFmHxx3tsIC&pg=PA43&dq=Annals+of+Quedlinburg+woman|publisher=Manchester Univ. Press|location=Manchester}}</ref> The annals are mostly dedicated to the history of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]; they also contain the first written mention of the [[name of Lithuania]] ("Litua"), dated to March, 1009. The original document has disappeared, surviving only as a 16th-century copy held in [[Dresden]],<ref>{{cite web|title=TO MARK THE MILLENNIUM OF LITHUANIA|publisher=Directorate for the Commemoration of the Millennium of Lithuania under the Auspices of the Office of the President of the Republic of Lithuania|url=http://www.lietuvai1000.lt/index.en.htm|accessdate=2008-09-02| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081003000131/http://www.lietuvai1000.lt/index.en.htm| archivedate= 3 October 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> but its contents endure as a scholarly resource.
==Background== [[File:Quedlinburg-Schlossberg ReiKi.jpg|thumb|225px|St. Servatius Church and the monastery]] The city of [[Quedlinburg]], Germany, was first mentioned in writing in a document dated to 922. [[Saint Mathilda]] founded a religious community for women at its [[Quedlinburg Abbey|abbey]], serving as abbess from 966 to 999.<ref name=warner/> The abbey became a premier educational institution for the female nobles of [[Saxony]], and maintained its mission for nearly 900 years.<ref name=FL>Felice Lifshitz. [http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=tmr;cc=tmr;q1=2006;rgn=main;view=text;idno=baj9928.0601.013 Die Annales Quedlinburgenses] Series: Monument Germaniae Historica, Scriptores Rerum Germanicarum In Usum Scholarum Separatim Editi vol. 72, 2004. Retrieved on 2008-09-01</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Quedlinburg UNESCO World Heritage |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |url=http://www3.quedlinburg.de/neu/englisch/Tourismus/geschichte.shtml |accessdate=2008-09-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616092955/http://www3.quedlinburg.de/neu/englisch/Tourismus/geschichte.shtml |archivedate=2008-06-16 }}</ref> The city served as an imperial [[Count palatine|palatinate]] of the Saxon emperors, where [[Henry the Fowler]], the founder of the [[Ottonian dynasty]], was buried.<ref name=AB>[[Alfredas Bumblauskas]]. Senosios Lietuvos istorija 1009-1795. 2005, p. 16 {{ISBN|9986-830-89-3}}</ref> Quedlinburg was situated not far from [[Magdeburg]], the Royal Assembly of the empire, and its annalists could therefore rely on genuine information from the royal house and obtain eyewitness accounts.<ref name=AB/> The city lost some stature under the rule of [[Henry II, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry II]], who broke with the tradition of celebrating Easter there; the Annals portray him unfavorably, and demonstrate the extent to which a royal monastery was entitled to criticize its monarch.<ref>{{cite book|last=Reuter|first=Timothy|author2=Rosamond McKitterick |author3=David Abulafia |year=1999|title=The New Cambridge Medieval History|publisher=Cambridge University Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u-SsbHs5zTAC&pg=RA1-PA291&lpg=RA1-PA291&dq=annals++quedlinburg | isbn=978-0-521-36447-8}}</ref>
==Annals== The Annals open with a chronicle of world history from the time of [[Adam]] to the [[Third Council of Constantinople]] in 680-681, based on chronicles by [[Jerome]], [[Isidore of Seville|Isidore]], and [[Bede]].<ref name=FL/> The narrative is largely borrowed from multiple older sources until the year 1002, although original reports from as early as 852 are present. Beginning in 993, the narrative begins including events which represent the annalist's own eyewitness testimony concerning events at and around Quedlinburg.<ref name=FL/> The amount of detail increases significantly from 1008 onwards, leading some analysts to conclude that 1008 was the actual date that the Annals were first compiled, although Robert Holzman argues for a start date of 1000.<ref name=chase>{{cite book|last=Chase|first=Colin|author-link=Colin Robert Chase|year=1997|title=The Dating of Beowulf|publisher=University of Toronto Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kWs1Wvp0otAC&pg=PA92&lpg=PA92&dq=annals++quedlinburg | isbn=978-0-8020-7879-7}}</ref> It has been suggested that the annalist temporarily abandoned the project between 1016 and 1021.<ref name=FL/> The exact reasons for this suspension of the work are unknown. Work on the project continued between 1021 and 1030, when its authors were able to report a military victory against [[Mieszko II]].
The primary task of the annalists was to record the heritage of the [[Ottonian dynasty]] and of Quedlinburg itself. The Annals incorporate the stories of a number of historic and legendary figures such as [[Attila the Hun]], King [[Dietrich of the Goths]], and others.<ref name=FL/> The historian [[Felice Lifshitz]] has suggested that the amount of [[saga]] material integrated into its narrative is without parallel.<ref name=FL/>
The Annals of Quedlinburg became an important research source; during the 12th century they were used by at least five contemporary historians. Felice Lifshitz asserts that the Annals of Quedlinburg played a key role in shaping the ways in which influential [[Germans]] of the 19th and 20th centuries saw their medieval past.<ref name=FL/> They continue to be analyzed in other contexts: by scholars of ''[[Beowulf]]'' discussing its use of the term ''Hugones'' to mean [[Franks]], by [[climate change|climatologists]], and in a book discussing fear of the [[Millennium (disambiguation)|millennium]].<ref name=chase/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Stothers |first=Richard B. |date=August 1998 |title=Far Reach of the Tenth Century Eldgjá Eruption, Iceland |journal=Climatic Change |volume=39 |issue=4 |accessdate=2008-09-02 |url=http://pubs.giss.nasa.gov/docs/1998/1998_Stothers_1.pdf |doi=10.1023/A:1005323724072 |pages=715 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111021085544/http://pubs.giss.nasa.gov/docs/1998/1998_Stothers_1.pdf |archivedate=2011-10-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Brody|first=Howard S.|year=2003|title=The Apocalyptic Year 1000: Religious Expectation and Social Change, 950-1050 |publisher=Oxford University Press |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SzS04SWI3G8C&pg=PA42&dq=Annals+of+Quedlinburg+1000 | isbn=978-0-19-511191-0}}</ref>
==Mention of Lithuania==
The first written occurrence of [[Lithuania]]'s [[Name of Lithuania|name]] has been traced to the Quedlinburg Annals and dated to 9 March 1009.<ref>{{cite journal | title=On the Origin of the Name of Lithuania | journal=Lituanus |url=http://www.lituanus.org/2009/09_3_02%20Baranauskas.html | volume=55 | issue=3 | date=Fall 2009 | first=Tomas | last=Baranauskas | issn=0024-5089}}</ref><ref>Richard C. Frucht. Eastern Europe. 2004. p.169 {{ISBN|1-57607-800-0}}</ref> The passage reads: {{cquote| Sanctus Bruno qui cognominatur Bonifacius archepiscopus et monachus XI. suæ conuersionis anno in confinio Rusciæ et Lituæ a paganis capite plexus cum suis XVIII, VII. Id. Martij petijt coelos.<ref>Albinus, Petrus Fabricius, Georg. [http://digital.slub-dresden.de/id287626156 Chronicon Quedlenburgense ab initio mundi per aetates]. Retrieved on 2013-09-05</ref>
"[In 1009] St. Bruno, an archbishop and monk, who was called Boniface, was slain by [[Pagan]]s during the 11th year of this conversion at the [[Rus (region)|Rus]] and [[Lithuania]]n border, and along with 18 of his followers, entered heaven on March 9th."}}
From other sources that describe [[Bruno of Querfurt]], it is clear that this missionary attempted to Christianize the pagan king [[Netimer]] and his subjects.<ref name=AB2>Alfredas Bumblauskas. [http://www.lietuvai1000.lt/nuorodos_pdf/Bumblauskas%20Lietuvos%20tukstantmetis.pdf Lietuvos tūkstantmetis – Millennium Lithuaniae]. Retrieved on 2009-09-01</ref> However, Netimer's brother, refusing to accept Christianity, killed Bruno and his followers. The historian [[Alfredas Bumblauskas]] has suggested that the story records the first [[Christianization of Lithuania|baptismal attempt]] in the [[history of Lithuania]].<ref name=AB2/>
